    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-02-14T13:25:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-02-14T13:00:00-05:00" n="240"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d240">
                <head>240. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d240fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives and Records Administration, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Williams Records, White House
                        Correspondence. Confidential. Drafted by Williams on March 2. The time is
                        taken from the President’s Daily Diary. (Johnson Library)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1964-02-14T13:00:00-05:00" to="1964-02-14T13:25:00-05:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">February 14, 1964, 1–1:25
                            p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Meeting at White House, February 14, 1964</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>The President</item>
                    <item>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Averell Harriman</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MWPJ1">William Mahoney</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BWH2">William Brubeck</persName>,</item>
                    <item>Assistant Secretary <persName corresp="#p_WGM1">G. Mennen
                            Williams</persName>,</item>
                    <item>McGeorge Bundy, Ralph Dungan, Edward Hutchinson</item>
                </list>
                <p>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> outlined the
                    Department’s position on the Ghana Situation and our feeling that for the United
                    States now to pull out of the Volta project in retaliation for recent Ghanaian
                    activities would be self defeating. Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MWPJ1"
                        >Mahoney</persName> made a few remarks.</p>
                <p>The gist of Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName>’s
                    remarks was that we were not coming to the President for instructions but rather
                    were advising him of the situation and the plan of action we would follow unless
                    he should choose to advise us to the contrary.</p>
                <p>The President took the briefing paper transmitted under cover of February 13th to
                    the Secretary and took up the items one by one.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Proposed Action Program</hi>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>He indicated a message would go to <persName corresp="#p_NK2"
                            >Nkrumah</persName> from the British Prime Minister.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>He thought it would be a good idea for Edgar Kaiser to see <persName
                            corresp="#p_NK2">Nkrumah</persName>.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>He agreed <persName corresp="#p_MWPJ1">Mahoney</persName> should see
                            <persName corresp="#p_NK2">Nkrumah</persName>.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>He said he didn’t know about the NIH but whatever we did was all
                        right.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>He said consultations could be undertaken with <gloss target="#t_IBRD1"
                            >IBRD</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>He would be agreeable to sending a letter to <persName corresp="#p_NK2"
                            >Nkrumah</persName> if and when it were decided to be advisable.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>President said he would be pleased to have Under Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> go to Accra as he had previously
                        indicated that he had hoped he would go to Africa.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
